00:28:45,923 --> 00:28:46,663
It's very simple, isn't it?

131
00:28:48,006 --> 00:28:54,513
The more angry you get about how the world is and all this business of climate change and all that, the more angry you become.

132
00:28:55,050 --> 00:29:05,387
The more you allow the mind to run away on its thoughts, the more it is developing the emotional state, which is the attitude, the attitude that you're developing.

133
00:29:07,010 --> 00:29:12,519
So, in our meditation, as soon as you wake up from the thought sequence, the dream sequence,

134
00:29:12,954 --> 00:29:15,799
It's telling you what is in the heart.

135
00:29:16,141 --> 00:29:17,222
Is it anger?

136
00:29:17,262 --> 00:29:18,144
Is it fear?

137
00:29:18,625 --> 00:29:19,886
Is it frustration?

138
00:29:19,906 --> 00:29:20,367
Whatever it is.

139
00:29:20,428 --> 00:29:21,309
Is it boredom?

140
00:29:21,329 --> 00:29:21,410
See?

141
00:29:21,851 --> 00:29:28,281
As soon as you know that, you come into the body and you contact directly the feeling of your emotion.

142
00:29:28,301 --> 00:29:29,403
You bury yourself in it.

143
00:29:29,443 --> 00:29:30,306
You feel it.

144
00:29:30,758 --> 00:29:43,906
I often come across people who've done lots of meditation who seem to have been instructed to see impermanence and to see the not-self and somehow the teaching around dukkha has been missing

